## FULL REVIEW (2026-06-13) — architect / dev / qa pass
Fresh three-persona pass over the current tree (does not repeat AR/CR/DX/G).
Findings prefixed ARCH-/DEV-/QA-.

### Architect
- [x] **ARCH-1. Duplicated `ToolResponse` type (12 copies)** — DONE 2026-06-13:
      the identical `{ isError; content: Array<{type;text}> }` shape was
      copy-pasted in all 11 mcp-server handlers plus `ToolHandlerResponse` in
      toolDispatch.ts — a silent drift surface. Consolidated into a leaf module
      `toolResponse.ts`; handlers import it, `ToolHandlerResponse` is now an
      alias. typecheck + lint green.
- [x] **ARCH-2. Other intra-mcp duplicated types** — DONE 2026-06-13: handlers
      now `import type` the canonical definitions — GraphNode/GraphEdge from
      analysis/graph.ts (3 handlers), CmdResult from processRunner (runtimeUtils
      + workspaceHandlers), UnifiedTaskType exported from toolService and
      imported by workflowHandlers. Each type has exactly one definition now;
      `import type` is erased at compile so zero runtime/cycle risk. check green.
- Confirmed healthy (no action): invariants #1 (no stdout pollution) and #2
  (both clients consume sn-transport for prefix/retry/endpoint-not-found, incl.
  CR18) hold; no cyclic/upward imports; handlers don't import index (§5). The
  only documented structural gap remaining is AR11 (module-level mutable state),
  left as tracked. (G10 boundaries are now machine-enforced via
  dependency-cruiser — 2026-06-21.)

### Dev
- [x] **DEV-1. No-op `catch (e) { throw e; }` blocks (12 sites)** — DONE
      2026-06-24. These wrapped a body in try/catch only to re-throw the same
      error: dead structure that obscures which code actually has error handling.
      The 3 in PluginManager.ts were fixed earlier (clean rewrite). The remaining
      9 (commands.ts downloadCommand/initCommand/deployCommand-inner,
      appUtils.ts processMissingFiles/swapScope/checkScope, wizard.ts setupDotEnv/
      writeDefaultConfig, FileUtils.ts) are now removed: outer no-op try unwrapped
      and bodies de-indented, while the genuine inner try/catch (scoped-endpoint
      fallback, best-effort gitignore, docs generation) is preserved untouched.
      Guarded against regression by enabling `no-useless-catch: error` in .eslintrc
      (the config extended only @typescript-eslint/recommended, so this rule was
      off). Typecheck + lint:core + full core suite (347 tests) green.
- [x] **DEV-2. `allSettled` reinvents native `Promise.allSettled`** — CLOSED
      2026-06-13 as won't-do: swapping to native changes the typed call sites
      (Sync.PromiseResult casts in appUtils) for zero behavior gain; the custom
      helper is harmless. Revisit only if that code is touched anyway.
### QA
- [x] **QA-1. Broken-config hard-fail was untested (invariant #6 / CR20)** —
      DONE 2026-06-13: config.ts throws "Failed to load config file" on a
      present-but-broken sync.config.js (never silently DEFAULT_CONFIG), but no
      test locked it — a refactor could quietly restore the dangerous default
      fallback. Added a regression test (syntactically broken config → rejects)
      to configValidation.test.ts. 5/5 green.
- [x] **QA-2. Thin handler coverage** — DONE 2026-06-21: added 5 per-handler
      test files (against dist, per the AR9 decision) for the weakest handlers —
      serviceNowCrud 2%→90%, scriptAnalysis 8%→100%, developerTool 10%→55%,
      metadataAnalysis 3%→42%, sessionHandlers 3%→40%. MCP line coverage
      82.6%→86.4%, 175→228 tests. Validation/guard/dry-run paths are covered
      without the network; happy-path network calls stay with the e2e suites.
- [x] **QA-3. Single-file `npx jest` from repo root** — DONE 2026-06-13:
      documented in CONTRIBUTING ("Running a single test file") — run from inside
      the package or via `npm --workspace`. Runner-resolution quirk, not a bug.
## DEEP DX RESEARCH — making the project exceptionally easy to use (2026-06-11)
Analysis of the whole journey from installation to daily development: CLI, Config,
Docs, Workflow, Error Handling, MCP.
**Focus: friction points that make even a "simple" task unpleasant for new users.**

### SETUP & ONBOARDING (DX1-DX4)

**DX1: The Windows WSL requirement is a trap**
- README: "preferably Windows Terminal and WSL (1903+)". This is buried and it is
  not clear that it is REQUIRED.
- 95% of Windows users do not have WSL installed and do not know how to set it up.
- [x] Add `syncrona check-env` — DONE 2026-06-13: new command checks Node (>=22),
      platform (flags native Windows, detects WSL), and Git, printing ✓/✗ per
      check with actionable fixes; exits non-zero on problems. Documented in
      README + CLAUDE.md (drift gate: 17 commands). e2e smoke test added.
- [x] Update README with a visible "⚠️ Windows users" section — DONE earlier
      (README Requirements now has the WSL-required callout).

**DX2: Credential store vs .env confusion**
- The user has 4 sources: env var, CredentialStore, .env, prompt. The fallback
  logic is invisible.
- The wizard does not show the final source — the user does not know where the
  credentials came from.
- Note 2026-06-12: precedence is now unified CLI↔MCP and documented in the mcp
  README (CR17); CLI-side visibility remains.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: `syncrona status` now prints "Credentials from: <source>"
      (credential store / instance profile env vars / environment (.env / shell)
      / none). Single internal resolver (resolveCredentialsInternal) reports
      both creds and source so precedence is never duplicated; new
      describeCredentialSource() + credentialSource in StatusSummary; 3 tests
      (credentialSource.test.ts). The test caught a real classification bug
      (base env mis-reported as profile) before it shipped.
- [x] "Found SN_INSTANCE in .env" — DONE 2026-06-14 (adapted to architecture):
      the no-.env path uses the credential STORE (logs "Using active
      CredentialStore profile for X"), not .env prompting; the .env path now
      names the instance ("Detected .env (SN_INSTANCE=X)…") and confirms before
      creating folders (DX4). The literal yes/no/enter-new prompt doesn't fit
      (wizard is store-based), so this captures the intent: never act on .env
      silently.

**DX3: Multi-instance workflow undocumented**
- `--instance-profile` is in help, but there are no examples; users have to guess
  the syntax.
- No guide for a dev+prod workflow or a safe context switch.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: docs/MULTI_INSTANCE.md — precedence, store vs profiles,
      dev→prod workflow, CI, troubleshooting. Linked from README + FAQ.

**DX4: Auto-init monorepo is unexpected**
- `syncrona init` with SN_* env vars creates `packages/x_*/` for all scopes.
- The user wonders why they suddenly have 10 new folders.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: auto-init (`init` with .env) now resolves the folder plan,
      prints "Found N scoped app(s). Would create under packages/: …", and
      confirms before creating anything. --ci skips the prompt; --dry-run reports
      the plan and creates nothing. 3 tests (commandsInitAuto).

---

### CLI INTERFACE (DX5-DX7)

**DX5: Help texts lack examples**
- `syncrona push --help` says "[DESTRUCTIVE]", which is scary, but shows no safe
  workflow examples.
- No `--dry-run` hint in help.
- [x] DONE 2026-06-13: added an `examples` field to the CliCommandModule
      registry (wired through buildCommandBuilder → yargs `.example()`); populated
      examples for dev/push/download/build/status/login/use/mcp, incl.
      `push --dry-run`, `push --diff main`, `push --ci`. Also set
      `.scriptName("syncrona")` so help shows `syncrona <cmd>` not `index.js`.
      e2e smoke test asserts `push --help` carries the examples.

**DX6: The `--diff` flag is unclear**
- CORRECTION 2026-06-13: the premise was wrong. `push --diff <branch>` already
  pushes ONLY the changed files (gitDiffToEncodedPaths → `git diff <branch>...`
  → getAppFileList over just those paths). It is already a changed-only push, so
  a separate `--changed-only` flag would just duplicate `--diff`. The real gap
  was clarity: `push --diff` = filter to changed files; `build --diff` = build
  all but write sync.diff.manifest.json for deploy.
- [x] ~~Add a --changed-only flag~~ — not needed (push --diff is the changed-only
  push). RESOLVED as a docs fix.
- [x] Document the two meanings — DONE 2026-06-13: README "Using the diff option"
  rewritten to contrast push vs build; --diff option describe and the push --diff
  help example corrected (the example previously mislabeled it as audit-only).

**DX7: `--instance-profile` on EVERY command is verbose**
- Typical work: `syncrona status --instance-profile dev`,
  `syncrona push --instance-profile dev`.
- The user has to remember the flag every time.
- [x] Add a `.syncrona-local` config — DONE 2026-06-13: a gitignored
      `.syncrona-local` (`{ "instanceProfile": "dev" }`) in the working dir sets a
      default profile; explicit --instance-profile still wins. resolveInstanceProfile
      in commandHelpers; 4 tests; documented in MULTI_INSTANCE.md; added to .gitignore.
- [x] Persist profile in `syncrona use` — N/A 2026-06-13: `use` selects the
      active *stored instance* (store-based); `.syncrona-local` sets the env-var
      *profile* default (DX7, done). Different mechanisms — not merged by design.

---

### CONFIGURATION COMPLEXITY (DX8-DX11)

**DX8: Plugin discovery requires manual names**
- The user must know the "TypeScript plugin" is called "@syncro-now-ai/typescript-plugin" on npm.
- `syncrona plugins` shows some but does not help when adding new plugins.
- [x] Add `config add-plugin` — DONE 2026-06-21: new action on the existing
      `config` command (so no new top-level command). With `--plugin <name>` it
      resolves the plugin (short alias / full pkg / loose form), reports
      installed-vs-missing, and prints the `npm i -D` command plus a paste-ready
      `rules` snippet; with no flag it lists all first-party plugins and their
      install status. Catalog + resolution + rendering are a pure module
      (pluginCatalog.ts); 16 tests (pluginCatalog.test.ts). README + CLAUDE.md
      updated.

**DX9: Default includes/excludes hidden in code**
- The "sane defaults" live in defaultManifestConfig.ts; users must read source
  code to understand them.
- [x] `syncrona status` should show "Active includes/excludes" — DONE 2026-06-13:
      status prints "Config rules: N include, M exclude (defaults + overrides)"
      from the merged config. (Per-rule defaults-vs-overrides provenance and a
      `config show-defaults` subcommand remain as a deeper follow-up.)
- [x] `syncrona config show-defaults` — DONE 2026-06-14: new `config <action>` command; show-defaults prints built-in sourceDirectory/buildDirectory/pushConcurrency/refreshInterval + default include/exclude rule counts. Documented (README+CLAUDE.md, 18 commands); e2e test.

**DX10: `sync.config.js` rule order matters, but there is no validation**
- README: "Order your rules by MOST SPECIFIC extension first!" — users can get the
  order wrong and silently fail.
- Note 2026-06-12: a broken config is now a hard fail instead of a silent default
  fallback (CR20), and option names/types are validated (G2); rule-order
  validation remains.
- [x] `syncrona build --check-config` — DONE 2026-06-13 (acb386e): validates rule
      order, reports any rule shadowed by an earlier broader one (synthesizes a
      representative filename from anchored patterns; zero false positives),
      exits non-zero without building. checkRuleOrder + 4 tests.
- [x] `--verbose build` — DONE 2026-06-13 (9c34412): processFile logs the matched rule per file at debug level.

**DX11: Advanced options undocumented (`displayField`, `differentiatorField`)**
- TableOptions get one line in the README. When to use them? What is
  `differentiatorField` for?
- "Will break the Windows filesystem" is a bad signal.
- [x] Document use cases — DONE 2026-06-13: README Table Options now has a
      "When to use each option" subsection explaining displayField (folder name
      field), differentiatorField (dedup of equal display values, with array
      fallback), and query (scope down large tables), plus a sharper Windows/WSL
      warning on differentiatorField.

